{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17636920","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17636920"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:35:22+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:35:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17613"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17613","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17613"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.78,0,0.07,0.16,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10327"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80516"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10327","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10327"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17613"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65805"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4932"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"6657"},{"type":"tags","id":"6668"},{"type":"tags","id":"7244"},{"type":"tags","id":"11230"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24160"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26008"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80516","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/80516"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe scalp receives its arterial blood supply from several vessels that anastomose to form a rich vascular network.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the major arteries supplying the superficial scalp?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Superficial temporal, occipital, and supratrochlear/supraorbital arteries","Angular, facial, and posterior auricular arteries","Internal carotid, vertebral, and basilar arteries","Middle meningeal, superficial temporal, and maxillary arteries","Deep temporal, masseteric, and occipital arteries"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe scalp receives its arterial blood supply from three main sources:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esuperficial temporal artery\u003C/strong\u003E (a terminal branch of the external carotid artery) supplies the lateral aspect of the scalp\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eoccipital artery\u003C/strong\u003E (a branch of the external carotid artery) supplies the posterior scalp\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esupratrochlear and supraorbital arteries\u003C/strong\u003E (terminal branches of the ophthalmic artery) supply the anterior scalp\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eangular and facial arteries\u003C/strong\u003E supply the face rather than the scalp\u003Cstrong\u003E, posterior auricular artery\u003C/strong\u003E has some supply to the scalp posterior to the ear, however given the other two vessels are incorrect, this is not the correct response\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Einternal carotid, vertebral, and basilar arteries\u003C/strong\u003E supply the brain rather than the scalp\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Emiddle meningeal, superficial temporal, and maxillary arteries\u003C/strong\u003E primarily supply deeper structures, with only the superficial temporal contributing to scalp supply\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Edeep temporal, masseteric, and occipital arteries\u003C/strong\u003E mainly supply the muscles of mastication, except for the occipital artery\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThese vessels form extensive anastomoses, creating a rich vascular network that explains why scalp wounds tend to bleed profusely.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The superficial temporal artery is a terminal branch of the external carotid artery that supplies the lateral scalp and temporal region.","The occipital artery arises from the external carotid artery and supplies the posterior scalp.","The supratrochlear and supraorbital arteries are terminal branches of the ophthalmic artery that supply the anterior scalp."],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin Terminology. Eighth edition. Elsevier; 2022.","Moore KL, Dalley AF, Agur A. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Lippincott Williams and Wilkins; 2017.","Nguyen JD, Duong H. Anatomy, Head and Neck, Posterior Auricular Artery. [Updated 2023 Jun 5]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK546687/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65805"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17613"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65805","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/65805"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-21T11:46:48+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-21T11:49:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10327"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80516"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":